    <questiontext format="markdown">
      <text><![CDATA[**31.4 E2 Newton-Raphson**

Consider a simple electronic circuit with an input voltage \\\(V_{in}\\\), a resistor \\\(R\\\) and a diode with saturation current \\\(I_s\\\) and thermal voltage \\\(V_{th}\\\) can be shown that the voltage \\\(V_D=x\\\) across the diode can be found as the single
positive zero of

\\\[ {@'f('x)=f(x)@}.\\\]

Calculate the derivative

\\\(f'(x)=\\\) [[input:S_df]] [[validation:S_df]] [[feedback:df]]

Find the zero for the following data:

- \\\({@V_in=ev(V_in, v)@}\,\rm{V}\\\)
- \\\({@R=ev(R, v)@}\,\rm{\Omega}\\\)
- \\\({@I_s=scientific_notation(ev(I_s, v),1)@}\,\rm{A}\\\)
- \\\({@V_th=ev(V_th, v)@}\,\rm{V}\\\)

<p>{@plot(ev(f(x),v), [x,0,0.8], [y,float(ev(f(0),v)),0.01], [xlabel,"x in V"], [ylabel,"f(x) in A"])@}</p>

Use the Newton-Raphson method with an initial value of {@'x0=x0@}. Perform the first two iterations:

\\\(x^{(1)}/\rm V=\\\) [[input:S_x1]], [[validation:S_x1]] [[feedback:x1]]

\\\(x^{(2)}/\rm V=\\\) [[input:S_x2]], [[validation:S_x2]] [[feedback:x2]]]]></text>
    </questiontext>
